V{{Infobox person\u000a|name          = Karla Jessen Williamson\u000a|image         = \u000a|image_size    = \u000a|caption       = \u000a|birth_date    = 1954\u000a|birth_place   = Appamiut, [[Maniitsoq]], [[Greenland]]\u000a|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\u000a|death_place   = \u000a|residence     = [[Calgary]], [[Canada]]\u000a|nationality   = \u000a|ethnicity     = [[Greenland]]ic [[Inuit]]\u000a|citizenship   = \u000a|known_for     = Executive Director,<br />[[Arctic Institute of North America]]\u000a|education     = [[University of Aberdeen]], [[Scotland]]\u000a|alma_mater    = \u000a|employer      = previously, [[University of Saskatchewan]]\u000a|occupation    = Educator, researcher\u000a|spouse        = Robert Gordon Williamson\u000a}}\u000a'''Karla Jessen Williamson''' (born 1954 in Appamiut, [[Maniitsoq]], [[Greenland]])<ref name="different">{{cite web|url=http://www.yukoncollege.yk.ca/~agraham/womensconf/1999/speakerbios.htm|title=Different Lives, Common Threads|date=1999-11-14|publisher=yukoncollege.yk.ca|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> is Executive Director of the [[Arctic Institute of North America]] (AINA), the first woman and first [[Inuit|Inuk]] to hold the position.<ref name="graham">{{cite web|url=http://www.yukoncollege.yk.ca/~agraham/womensconf/nwnotable3.htm|title=Notable Northern Women: Elders/Teachers/Scholars/Scientists|last=Graham|first=Amanda |date=2006-09-11|publisher=yukoncollege.yk.ca|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> Fluent in [[Danish language|Danish]], [[English language|English]], and [[Greenlandic language|Greenlandic]],<ref name="contributor" /><ref name="message">{{cite web|url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/aina/AINAAR2000.pdf|title=Message from the Acting Executive Director|last=Dickerson|first=Mark O.|publisher=ucalgary.ca|pages=3|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> she is an educator and researcher on [[cross-culturalism]],<ref name="different" /> [[multiculturalism]], [[antiracism]], and Aboriginal [[epistemology]].<ref name="roots">{{cite web|url=http://www.mcgill.ca/resilience/people/collaborators/|title= ICIHRP Roots of Resilience Project |date=2008-10-06 |publisher=mcgill.ca|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Early years==\u000aWilliamson, a [[Kalaallit|Kalaaleq]], was born in Greenland, and received her primary education there.  She graduated from high school in Denmark.  She received her bachelor's degree and her master's degree in Education<ref name="contributor">{{cite web|url=http://www.banffcentre.ca/Press/contributors/vwxyz/williamson_k/|title=Karla Jessen Williamson, Contributor|year=2008|publisher=banffcentre.ca|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> from the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in [[Canada]], and her Ph.D. from the Department of [[Anthropology]], [[University of Aberdeen]] in Scotland.<ref name="roots" /><ref name="dickerson" />\u000a\u000a==Career==\u000aWilliamson's research includes [[Inuit]] [[childbearing]] and [[gender roles]] in [[post-colonial]] Greenland.<ref name="stern">{{cite book|last=Stern|first=Pamela R. |title=Historical Dictionary of the Inuit|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2004|pages=154|isbn=0-8108-5058-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3UHTsUmt1PEC&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=%22karla+jessen+williamson%22}}</ref> She taught for sixteen years in the Indian and Northern Education program at the University of Saskatchewan before moving to the AINA on 15 September 2000.<ref name="dickerson">{{cite journal|last=Dickerson|first=Mark O.|date=June 2000|title=The Challenge of Change |journal=Arctic |publisher=ucalgary.ca |volume=53 |issue=2\u000a|url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic53-2-iii.pdf |doi=10.14430/arctic840}}</ref>  She is also a Senior Researcher with the [[Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pre.ethics.gc.ca/english/pdf/PRE_NCEHR_Program_2006.pdf|title=Engaging Voices: a Season of Consultations on the TCPS|date=2006-02-17|work=Interagency Advisory Panel on Research Ethics|publisher=pre.ethics.gc.ca|pages=2|accessdate=2008-10-24}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\u000a\u000aBecause of her role with the Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami and the [[Arctic]] Human Health Initiative,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arctichealth.org/ahhi/proposals/projects/cehh_arctic-resiliency_fp.htm |title=Changing Environment & Human Health |year=2006 |publisher=arctichealth.org |accessdate=2008-10-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106113731/http://www.arctichealth.org/ahhi/proposals/projects/cehh_arctic-resiliency_fp.htm |archivedate=January 6, 2009 }}</ref> Williamson became the Activity Leader for the [[International Polar Year|IPY]] 2007-2008 project "Arctic Resiliency and Diversity: Community Response to Change" in collaboration with the [[Inuit Circumpolar Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://classic.ipy.org/development/eoi/proposal-details.php?id=183|title=Full Proposals for IPY 2007-2008 Activities|publisher=ipy.org|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> She is a notable presenter on [[mask]]ing and promotes it for Inuit understanding of [[gender equality]] in relationship to [[ancestors]], animals, and the environment. In addition, Williamson has been an editor for the\u000a[[Gabriel Dumont Institute]]'s ''Journal of Indigenous Studies''.<ref name="different" />\u000a\u000a==Personal life==\u000aWilliamson was married to Dr. Robert Gordon Williamson (1931-2012, [[Oxley, Wolverhampton]], [[Staffordshire]], [[England]]), an anthropologist, and [[Professor Emeritus]] at the University of Saskatchewan.<ref name="fonds">{{cite web|url=http://scaa.usask.ca/gallery/northern/en_finding_aid_display.php?filename=williamson&title=Robert%20Williamson%20fonds|title=RG Williamson fonds|publisher=usask.ca|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>  They have two children.<ref name="dickerson" /> Karla is currently living near Saskatoon and working as assistant professor in the Department of Educational Foundations as the University of Saskatchewan.<ref name="message" />\u000a\u000a==Quote==\u000a{{quote|The Arctic is really the canary in the coal mine in terms of [[climate change]].|Williamson, 2003<ref name="urquhart">{{cite news|url=http://www.ucalgary.ca/oncampus/weekly/oct17-03/dew-line.html|title=From DEW-line to Sea Lane|last=Urquhart|first=Dennis |date=2003-10-17|publisher=ucalgary.ca|accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>}}\u000a\u000a==Partial bibliography==\u000a* Jessen Williamson, Karla(2011) Inherit my Heaven: Kalaalit Gender Relations. Inussuk, Nuuk.\u000a* Williamson, K. J. (1987). "Consequence of Schooling: Cultural Discontinuity amongst the Inuit". ''Canadian Journal of Native Education''. 14 (2), 60-69. OCLC 93453172\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [http://www.usask.ca/education/people/jessen-williamson.htm Photo]\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, Karla Jessen}}\u000a[[Category:1954 births]]\u000a[[Category:Greenlandic emigrants to Canada]]\u000a[[Category:Greenlandic women]]\u000a[[Category:Greenlandic Inuit people]]\u000a[[Category:University of Saskatchewan alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\u000a[[Category:University of Saskatchewan faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Epistemologists]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]
